Figs 6-8. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cunha &amp; Sousa-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Cunha &amp; Sousa-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[235,360,1927,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Lizerius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jorgei" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[235,360,1927,1945]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Lizerius jorgei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[367,437,1927,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, alate viviparous female: 6, body and wings (100x magnification); 7, hind tarsus (400x magnification); 8, antennae (400x magnification).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,775,154,503]" lastBlockId="3.[813,1437,154,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,456,381,405]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Alatemale specimen.</emphasis>
Alive aphids with vivid yellow color, dark brown thorax; compound eyes black and red triommatidium. Specimens cleared and mounted in slides present body completely membranous with the thoracic region darker than in females, very dark legs and last rostral segment with small sclerotization.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[813,1437,154,503]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[888,1181,219,243]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Morphological characters.</emphasis>
Characteristics based on the analysis of one alate male form (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1309,251,275]" captionStart="Figs 9, 10" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[223,1359,549,1532]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1407,533,1552]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9, 10. Lizerius jorgei sp. nov., alate male: 9, body and wings (100x magnification); 10, antennae (400x magnification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677361/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs 9, 10</figureCitation>
). Body pale with dark thoracic region and very dark legs. It differs from alate females by having high number of secondary rhinaria and several rhinaria in V and VI antennal segments, which are similar in size and shape of rhinaria present at segment III; and by possessing Vantennal segment slightly larger than females (
<figureCitation box="[963,1044,446,470]" captionStart="Figs 9, 10" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[223,1359,549,1532]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1407,533,1552]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9, 10. Lizerius jorgei sp. nov., alate male: 9, body and wings (100x magnification); 10, antennae (400x magnification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677361/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Body slightly smaller than females (
<figureCitation box="[821,886,479,503]" captionStart="Figs 9, 10" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1567,1586]" captionTargetBox="[223,1359,549,1532]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1407,533,1552]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 9, 10. Lizerius jorgei sp. nov., alate male: 9, body and wings (100x magnification); 10, antennae (400x magnification)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677361/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Other features similar to alate viviparous females.
</paragraph>
